[[File:Lighttrap.jpg|thumb|Hunting birds by night]]
'''Bat-fowling''' is an archaic method of catching [[bird]]s at night,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rd.com/slideshows/8-amusing-stories-behind-common-expressions/5/ |title=8 Amusing Stories Behind Common Expressions &#124; Reader's Digest |publisher=Rd.com |date=2011-11-13 |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref> while they are at [[Bird#Resting and roosting|roost]]. The process involves lighting straw or torches near their roost. After awakening them from their roost, the birds fly toward the flames, where, being amazed, they are easily caught in nets, or beaten with bats. The phrase "beating about the bush" is said to be derived from this practice as the [[Trapping|trapper's]] accomplices would go around the bushes to disturb the birds.<ref>{{cite book|title=2107 curious word origins, sayings and expressions from white elephants to a song and dance|author=Funk, Charles Earle|authorlink=Charles Earle Funk|year= |isbn=0-88365-845-3| page=76}}</ref> The practice was also called '''lanciatoia''' in [[Italy]] and a variation was called '''low-belling'''. The low-belling process involves approaching birds with bright lights and using [[Cowbell|cow bells]], which the birds were accustomed to, to approach the birds up close and capture them with a long-handled [[Net (device)|net]].<ref>{{cite book|author= Macpherson HA |year=1897| title= A history of fowling|place= Edinburgh|publisher= David Douglas|page=60| url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924000125256}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The sportsman's dictionary; or the Gentleman's companion: for town and country| place=London|year=1878|publisher=Fielding and Walker|url= https://archive.org/stream/sportsmansdictio00lond#page/n46/mode/1up}}</ref>

